04471nam a22005055i 9780773562943DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19911991xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735629437 a10.1515/97807735629432doi  a(DE-B1597)655635  a(OCoLC)732600965  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aHN103.5bW47 1991eb 7aPOL0400002bisacsh04a320.4711 aWhitaker, Reg, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSovereign Idea :bEssays on Canada as a Democratic Community /cReg Whitaker. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1991] 4c©1991  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tClass and Community -- tImages of the State in Canada -- tThe Liberal Corporatist Ideas of Mackenzie King -- tWilliam Irvine and the Farmers in Politics -- tLiberalism and Nationality -- t"To Have Insight into Much and Power Over Nothing": The Political Ideas of Harold Innis -- tReason, Passion, and Interest: Pierre Trudeau's Eternal Liberal Triangle -- tFederalism and Democracy -- tFederalism and Democratic Theory -- tDemocracy and the Canadian Constitution -- tDemocracy and Community -- tFederalism, Democracy, and the Canadian Political Community -- tBetween Patronage and Bureaucracy: Democratic Politics in Transition -- tQuebec and the Canadian Constitution -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn these essays, written during the last fifteen years, Whitaker analyses the paradoxes of federalism and democracy in a society which is deeply divided by region, language, and class. He examines the thought and action of such diverse figures as Mackenzie King, Harold Innis, William Irvine, and Pierre Trudeau and evaluates their impact on Canadian society both then and now. With an astute critical eye he surveys constitutional reform and the question of Quebec sovereignty as it has developed from 1981 through Meech Lake and beyond, and explores federalism, democratic theory, and the practice of politics in the real world. In the final essay, "Quebec and the Canadian Question," written especially for this volume, he evaluates the major changes which have occurred in Canadian politics during the last fifteen years and assesses their resounding impact on the future possibilities for Canadian democracy. The dominant political discourse, Whitaker argues, is increasingly based on human rights. This, in combination with the ascendance of free-market conservatism, the turn to continentalism under free trade, and the resurgence, since the failure of Meech Lake, of serious tensions between Quebec and the rest of Canada, has led to a compounded crisis that requires an examination not only of what Quebec wants, with or without Canada, but what Canada wants -- with or without Quebec. The Canadian idea of democracy is still evolving. Together in one volume for the first time, Whitaker's essays describe the process of that evolution and show what lies beneath the constitutional debate on the future of Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / American Government / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356294340uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773562943423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773562943/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles